<br />
This is of course true, but what Mother Nature can throw at us is not trivial by any means.  Global warming can and does obviously melt the ice caps which changes the consistency of the water around it.  A significant change in consistency can and would cause significantly different weather patterns around the world.  The ice caps also, or so I have read, actually sit on top of a "slushy" layer of ice and water due to all the pressure caused by their massive weight.  A significant change in temperature could conceivably change the balance enough for a large portion of the ice cap to literally slide off into the ocean and that would significantly drop the ocean temperature.
<br />

<br />
I'll admit that I do not know a hell of a lot about it, but there have been theories I have read about how global warming can actually over time cause us to fall into another ice age, and I don't think I need to state how devastating that would be.  Really, if it is us humans that are causing a significant amount of pollution which in turn causes global warming, this is not going to change, so we will find out one way or the other what happens...</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
