			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Where did you get that information? Do you really think that is the reason the Dark Ages ended? Hope it doesn't totally derail the thread, but I couldn't let this little morsel slip by unchallenged.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Obviously there were many factors.  This may have been a very important one.
<br />

<br />
It a theory I have read about several times.  Sorry but I don't have any references handy.  It comes from juxtaposition of human history and global climate.  Consider Greenland, so called because when the Vikings found it, it was green, lush, and fertile.  The climate was in a warm period.  Then came a mini ice age (we have them all the time, climatically speaking) and food slowly could no longer be grown there and the community there shrunk and died.
<br />

<br />
The beginning of the Dark Ages seems to coincide with a mini ice age.  Food was harder to grow, thus harder to come by.  There were no resources to spare, everyone was concerned with putting food on the table.  The end of the Dark Ages coincides with a warming climate, food more plentiful, extra resources to put into activities resulting in the Renaissance.  (Which led to the Reformation, God moves in mysterious ways, lol.)
<br />

<br />
Consider Hadrian's Wall.  He put it where it is because you could grow grapes up to that point and it was therefore not worth the effort to go farther north.  (Odd note, the Roman Empire never desired to expand farther north than you could grow grapes.  Wine was very important to that culture.  Arguably for sound sanitation reasons.)  The climate was in a warm period in the heyday of the Empire.  I defy you to grow grapes just south of Hadrian's Wall today.
<br />

<br />
Hopefully, my memory hasn't misrepresented the theory.<br />_________________<br />Once a Prophet.......
